From: Peios <kernel@peios.org>
Subject: FACS patch 5: skip credential swap in do_faccessat

On Peios, setuid does not exist. Identity is token-based. The
credential swap in access()/faccessat() causes FACS to evaluate
the primary token instead of the effective token, inverting the
intent when a service is impersonating a client.

Fix: add a new LSM hook security_access_use_effective() that
returns nonzero if access() should use the effective token
(skip the credential swap). KACS always returns true.

--- a/include/linux/lsm_hook_defs.h
+++ b/include/linux/lsm_hook_defs.h
@@ -212,6 +212,7 @@
 LSM_HOOK(int, 0, file_truncate, struct file *file)
+LSM_HOOK(int, 0, access_use_effective, void)
--- a/include/linux/security.h
+++ b/include/linux/security.h
@@ -570,6 +570,7 @@
 int security_file_truncate(struct file *file);
+int security_access_use_effective(void);
--- a/security/security.c
+++ b/security/security.c
@@ -3200,6 +3200,11 @@
 }

+int security_access_use_effective(void)
+{
+	return call_int_hook(access_use_effective);
+}
+
--- a/fs/open.c
+++ b/fs/open.c
@@ -389,6 +389,10 @@
 {
 	const struct cred *cred;

+	/* KACS: always use effective token (§14.3 patch 5). */
+	if (security_access_use_effective())
+		return false;
+
 	if (flags & AT_EACCESS)
 		return false;
